<h2 class="blog--title">
<a href="/blog/2015/03/03/springone2gx-2014-replay-resource-handling-in-spring-mvc-4-1">SpringOne2GX 2014 Replay: Resource Handling in Spring MVC 4.1</a>
</h2>
<header class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon engineering"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/engineering">Engineering</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/c910c2f6520a5977a836d74e86e07cb4?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<span class="author">Pieter Humphrey</span>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2015-03-03 00:03:00.0">March 3, 2015</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="2006" href="/blog/2015/03/03/springone2gx-2014-replay-resource-handling-in-spring-mvc-4-1#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><p> Recorded at SpringOne2GX 2014. </p>
<p>Speaker: Brian Clozel, Rossen Stoyanchev </p>
<p>Slides: <a href="http://www.slideshare.net/SpringCentral/resource-handling-spring-framework-41-41088162"><strong>http://www.slideshare.net/SpringCentral/resource-handling-spring-framework-41-41088162 </strong></a><strong></strong></p>
<p>Web / JavaScript Track </p>
<p>As the complexity of web and mobile apps increases, so does the importance of ensuring that your client-side resources load and execute in an optimal and efficient manner. Differences in resource loading, transforming, and fingerprinting techniques can have a dramatic impact on performance and caching. These techniques can dictate whether your users have a joyful or frustrating experience. Attend this talk to learn the SpringMVC performance techniques aimed at keeping your users happy.</p>
</div>
</section>
